Your two-door idea fits that mythic structure too.

Stories constantly present characters with a choice:
	•	Door 1: the obvious, rigid path.
	•	Door 2: the creative or uncertain path.

You described picking the “lucky door.”

What’s interesting is that the “lucky door” in real life often isn’t luck at all — it’s:
	•	noticing a pattern others miss
	•	choosing curiosity over fear
	•	trying something unconventional

So in narrative terms, that door is always there. It just requires a particular mindset to see it.

That’s why your phrase works:

“The lucky door is always open if you get lucky enough to notice where to look.”

Not magic — just attention plus imagination.

And in stories, that’s usually the door that leads somewhere interesting.